add a new modifier Demon Lord
Eshalurd will gain 0.07% health and mana regeneration for every enemys in a 750 radius around him and also giving 3% spellamp and attack
damage when they die as well for 25 seconds, each stacks got their own durations. If Eshalurd is under Hells Flames he will increase
Dooming Slash damage by 50% and LVL? Death by 35% for its duration and also making them spellvamp for 15% of the damage dealt. Eshalurd
will gain a stack of Demonology for every enemys that die around him, each stack will give 0.04 health regeneration and 1 health, max of
500 stacks. At 70 stacks, Eshalurd will gain 13% health and increase the bonus Agility and Strenght from DoomBringer by 4%. At 205 stacks,
Eshalurd will gain a 12% spellvamp with 6% spellamp and attack damage aura for him and his allys in a 900 radius and also increase the
spellamp gain per level by 0.10%. At 390 stacks, increase the health regeneration bonus scaling by 6% from DoomBringer and increase
Eshalurd Size by 35%, gaining 15% status resistence and 10% damage reduction. All stacks are lost on Death.


ULTIMATE Doomed Soul
Eshalurd doom his target into agony, dealing insane Pure amount of damage every 2.0 seconds each tick reducing the target pure resistence
and movespeed with attack speed. It also silence the target making them unable to cast spells even if they are magic immune and if they
are magic immune, they will suffer 25% increase damage from Doomed and the damage over time will change to 1.0 seconds instead of dealing
damage every 2.0 seconds. When a target enemy is affected by Doomed Soul, Eshalurd will become magic immune and also gaining bonus attack
damage, spellamp and evasion over the duration of Doomed Soul. Doomed Soul will become active at level 9 and will upgrade at level 17 28.
the debuff attack speed, movespeed and pure resist lost will last 3.5 seconds and will refresh for every tick of damage. Doomed Soul will
have 1.2% mana cost increase for every levels of Eshalurd. Doomed Soul will ignore all from of Status resistence.

